# Notion, Obsidian, and the Architecture of an AI Chief of Staff

*I built a Claude-powered Chief of Staff on Obsidian over several months. Before publishing the system, I wanted to know whether my tool choice was right, or whether I'd landed somewhere and rationalized it after the fact. Most Notion-versus-Obsidian comparisons are written by people fluent in one tool and generous toward the other. This one is written by someone who built a working system in Obsidian, spent real time inside Notion, and is willing to say what each one does badly.*

## The question

People who see this system ask two things. How does it work, which the rest of this repository answers. And could it be built in Notion, where most knowledge workers already live.

The second question deserves a real answer. Notion is not a worse Obsidian. Obsidian is not a worse Notion. They come from different companies, funded on different models, solving adjacent but distinct problems. The difference changes what you would want to build on top of them.

## Two companies, two bets

Obsidian is a local-first markdown editor. Your notes are plain text files on your hard drive. The app reads them, connects them, and otherwise stays out of the way. There is no cloud by default. The company employs seven people, has taken no venture capital, and carries a valuation of roughly three hundred and fifty million dollars, built entirely on user subscriptions. It has no investors to answer to and no pressure to monetize your data.

Notion is a cloud-based workspace. Your pages live on Notion's servers. The company employs close to six thousand people, has raised four hundred and eighteen million from Sequoia and Accel, is valued at eleven billion, and is on a path toward a public offering in 2026. It serves a hundred million users, including seventy percent of the Fortune 500.

These are not equivalent companies building equivalent tools. The divergence in scale, capital structure, and trajectory shows up downstream in every product decision they make, including the ones that will affect your data a decade from now.

## Why the business model matters

Obsidian's local-first architecture is a privacy feature. It's also a business model. Because files live on your machine, operational costs are near zero. That's how a seven-person team serves millions of users profitably without outside capital. The absence of venture funding removes the usual incentive gradient. No exit pressure, no quarterly growth targets, no monetization of stored data. Revenue comes from optional sync and publish subscriptions. The core product is free and will stay that way.

Notion's model is different. At six hundred million in ARR, growing at fifty percent annually, they are building toward a public exit. Public companies answer to shareholders in ways that flow downstream over time through pricing changes, feature paywalling, and data strategy. This isn't a criticism. It's the rational behavior of a well-funded firm doing what well-funded firms do. But if the tool is an operating system you intend to use for the next decade, it's worth knowing what you are betting on.

## The pricing, clearly

Notion's tiers are Free (limited AI trial that cuts off at unspecified usage), Plus at ten dollars per user per month (basic writing assistance only), and Business at eighteen dollars per user per month billed annually. Full AI access, Agents, Ask Notion, and Custom Agents live at the Business tier. Full Notion AI runs about two hundred and sixteen dollars a year per user.

The Obsidian plus Claude stack looks like this. Obsidian itself is free. The commercial license is fifty dollars a year. Optional Sync is another forty-eight. Claude Pro is two hundred and forty. Roughly two hundred and ninety to three hundred and forty dollars a year per user, depending on whether you want Sync.

The gap is smaller than most people think. And the second stack gives you a meaningfully more capable model.

## The Claude partnership inside Notion

This point is underreported, and it changes the shape of the comparison.

Notion and Anthropic have a formal partnership. Inside Notion 3.2, you can select Claude Opus 4.7 as your model, alongside GPT-5.2 and Gemini 3, and assign tasks to Claude directly from a Notion task board.

At the Business tier, you're paying eighteen dollars a month to access Claude through Notion's interface, subject to Notion's workspace-search layer. Twenty dollars a month to Anthropic puts Claude directly on your files with no intermediary.

For teams that need Notion's collaboration surface, the partnership is a real feature. For a solo operator, it is a middleman.

## What each AI does well

Notion AI is strong at several things. Meeting-note summarization is consistently excellent. Inline writing assistance is fast and context-aware. Database autofill enriches rows continuously without manual intervention. The Notion Agent can work autonomously for up to twenty minutes on multi-step goals. Calendar, mail, and Slack integrations are native and functional.

It gets worse at the one function that matters most for a Chief of Staff. Question-and-answer synthesis across a workspace. Accuracy holds up when the answer lives on a single page and drops noticeably the moment the question requires pulling across multiple pages. The most cited complaint on Notion's subreddit describes the structural problem with unusual precision: "The biggest problem is that it doesn't know your workspace, it just searches it. If it had your workspace loaded in its context the usefulness would be 100% better." The model also occasionally produces content that doesn't exist in the workspace, and its writing quality rates lower than Claude's in independent blind comparisons.

Claude reading an Obsidian vault is a different kind of operation. It doesn't search-and-rank. It reads files directly through MCP, follows the links between them, and holds what it pulls in full context. The ceiling is the context window, not a retrieval score, and on recent Claude versions that window is large enough to hold an entire personal vault. In independent reviews, Claude scored substantially higher than Notion AI on reasoning depth and analytical quality.

The structural summary. Notion AI searches your workspace. Claude reads it. The distinction is invisible on small questions and decisive on the ones a Chief of Staff is meant to answer.

## Privacy and data ownership

Notion's handling of customer data is solid for a cloud service. Data lives on Notion's servers. Models are not trained on your content by default. Contractual agreements prevent subprocessors from using your data for model training. Enterprise users get zero data retention with LLM providers. Non-enterprise users have their data deleted within thirty days. Offline mode exists but is severely limited. Only the first fifty database rows sync, AI features are disabled offline, and data can be lost if you stay offline for more than thirty days.

Obsidian's model is different. Files live on your machine. There is no default cloud dependency. With a local language model via Ollama, the entire system becomes air-gapped. No external data transmission, the model running on your own hardware. If Obsidian ceased to exist tomorrow, every file would remain where it is, readable in any text editor.

There is a meaningful difference between "we promise not to use your data" and "your data never leaves your device." For a system that accumulates sensitive business context, client material, and a decade of decisions, that distinction deserves to be stated, not glossed.

## The ecosystem gap

Obsidian hosts 2,754 community plugins and 416 themes as of 2026. The most-downloaded plugins (Excalidraw at 5.8 million installs, Templater at 4 million, Dataview at 3.9 million, Tasks at 3.3 million) are serious standalone products. One hundred and eleven plugin updates shipped in a single ten-day stretch this March. The subreddit has two hundred thousand members. The Discord has a hundred and ten thousand.

Notion has no plugin ecosystem. It is a closed platform with official connectors to Salesforce, Box, Slack, GitHub, and a handful of others. Deep customization in Notion is whatever Notion decides to build. Deep customization in Obsidian is whatever two thousand developers have decided to build, which turns out to be a great deal.

One example worth naming. The Smart Connections plugin powers semantic search across your vault using the same vector-embedding techniques behind commercial RAG systems, surfacing non-obvious relationships between notes. There is no Notion equivalent, and the gap is not obviously closable.

## Migration is asymmetric

Notion to Obsidian is easy. Export as an HTML archive, run the Obsidian Importer plugin, done. The migration path is clean and well-trodden.

Obsidian to Notion is the hard direction. The md2notion tool exists but frequently times out or throws errors. Notion's native markdown import loses data. Wikilinks do not transfer. Backlinks do not transfer. Plugin-generated metadata does not transfer. The graph structure you built over months does not transfer. This is the standard outcome of moving between systems with different structural assumptions.

The deeper issue is format longevity. Obsidian files are plain text markdown, readable in any text editor in thirty years regardless of whether Obsidian still exists. Notion stores content in a proprietary database. Current exports work in the common case, but complex pages don't always translate cleanly to other tools, and the risk compounds as your system grows. Markdown predates Notion by more than a decade and will outlast it.

## Where Notion wins

Real-time collaboration is not close. Notion handles simultaneous editing natively. Multiple cursors, instant changes, no merge conflicts, inline comments, @-mentions, guest access, granular permissions. Obsidian shared vaults rely on a diff-match-patch merge algorithm with no file locking. Two people editing the same note at the same time produces conflicts that require manual resolution. If a team needs to inhabit the same system at once, Notion is the correct choice by a wide margin.

Day-one experience is also better. Notion works the moment you sign up. No markdown syntax to learn, no plugins to configure, no vault to design. The learning curve for the system in this repository was months, and I wouldn't pretend otherwise.

Mobile is cleaner. Notion's mobile app loads in roughly two seconds on a recent phone, runs AI transcription in the background, and approximates desktop functionality. Obsidian's mobile app is capable but expects a user who already knows the ecosystem.

Structured data is more mature. Six native database views, a decade of refinement, real formulas, rollups, and filters. If the use case is a CRM or editorial calendar, Notion is simply better at it today.

Templates are more accessible. Notion's marketplace offers hundreds of polished one-click templates. Obsidian's equivalents are scattered across GitHub and forums. The Notion experience is faster. The Obsidian experience is more customizable. A genuine tradeoff.

## The database gap is narrowing

Worth watching. Obsidian's Bases feature, rolling out through 2025 and 2026, layers structured database views directly onto the existing vault without creating separate databases. It queries the notes you already have and imposes structure on demand, supporting table and card views, inline editing, relations, and rollups.

The philosophical contrast is worth naming. Notion databases are containers you build and then fill. Bases surfaces structure that already exists in the notes you have written. As Bases matures, the database gap between the two tools will narrow substantially. It is not closed yet.

## A capability with no Notion equivalent

Obsidian's graph view maps every connection between your notes visually. Each note is a node, each link an edge. As the system grows it draws a rough map of your own thinking.

The underlying concept is emergent structure. Architecture that arises from sustained attention rather than upfront design. The InfraNodus plugin adds genuine network-science analysis on top, using betweenness centrality to identify the concepts that dominate your graph and the topical clusters that should be connected but are not.

Notion has no equivalent. Its structure is hierarchical. Pages inside databases inside pages. That is a good structure for organized people. It does not reveal what you did not know you were thinking.

## The architecture almost nobody has built

The most useful insight from running this system is that Notion and Obsidian are not mutually exclusive. They answer different questions.

The architecture that makes sense for most consultants and small teams:

- **The personal layer on Obsidian.** Memory files, session logs, task system, strategic thinking, decision history. Local, plain-text, yours. This is where Claude lives and writes.
- **The shared layer on Notion.** Client workspaces, collaborative documents, team materials, meeting notes the whole team edits together.
- **Claude bridging both through MCP.** With the Notion connector installed, the model reads your Notion workspace the same way it reads your vault. One model, two data sources, a single coherent assistant.

Personal layer in Obsidian. Team layer in Notion. One model reading both. This is the architecture I would recommend to most consultants and small teams, and it is nearly absent from public writing on AI-assisted work because almost nobody has built it end to end.

## Recommendations by situation

*If you need something working this week.* Use Notion. Install the Notion MCP connector. Functional in an afternoon, adequate for most people.

*If you are building a long-term personal system.* Use Obsidian. The up-front cost is real. The payoff is a knowledge base that compounds, lives on your hardware, and gives the model full context every session.

*If you serve clients or run a small team.* Use both. Personal layer in Obsidian, team layer in Notion, Claude bridging them through MCP.

*If you are already deep in Notion.* Stay there and install the connector. Migration is painful enough that it is usually not worth it unless the synthesis problem is actively costing you real time.

*If privacy is the point.* Obsidian with a local model via Ollama is the only serious option. Notion cannot match it by design.

## One line

Notion is a better tool for working with other people. Obsidian is a better tool for thinking with a model. For a personal AI Chief of Staff, the question reduces to whether you want your AI to search your system or know it.

